04329nam a22007935i 9780271086293DE-B159720230328044521.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230328t20202019pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710862937 a10.1515/97802710862932doi  a(DE-B1597)584214  a(OCoLC)1257324930  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aML420.B6856 7aMUS0200002bisacsh04a782.421660922231 aSeales, Chad E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReligion Around. Religion Around Bono :bEvangelical Enchantment and Neoliberal Capitalism /cChad E. Seales. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2020] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aReligion Around ;v700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Evangelicalism Around -- t2. Around Bono -- t3. Neoliberalism Around -- t4. Around Africa -- t5. Love and Debt -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor many, U2’s Bono is an icon of both evangelical spirituality and secular moral activism. In this book, Chad E. Seales examines the religious and spiritual culture that has built up around the rock star over the course of his career and considers how Bono engages with that religion in his music and in his activism.Looking at Bono and his work within a wider critique of white American evangelicalism, Seales traces Bono’s career, from his background in religious groups in the 1970s to his rise to stardom in the 1980s and his relationship with political and economic figures, such as Jeffrey Sachs, Bill Clinton, and Jesse Helms. In doing so, Seales shows us a different Bono, one who uses the spiritual meaning of church tradition to advocate for the promise that free markets and for-profits will bring justice and freedom to the world’s poor. Engaging with scholarship in popular culture, music, religious studies, race, and economic development, Seales makes the compelling case that neoliberal capitalism is a religion and that Bono is its best-known celebrity revivalist.Engagingly written and bitingly critical, Religion Around Bono promises to transform our understanding of the rock star’s career and advocacy. Those interested in the intersection of rock music, religion, and activism will find Seales’s study provocative and enlightening.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aEvangelicalism. 0aNeoliberalismxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 7aMUSIC / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aAfrica.  aBono.  aCapitalism.  aCorporate Philanthropy.  aEvangelicalism.  aGlobalization.  aNeoliberalism.  aReligion.  aRevivalism.  aU2.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311074520740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271086293?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271086293423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271086293/original  a978-3-11-074520-7  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK